article.description:
Ben Gordon scored 29 points and Emeka Okafor added 19 Saturday, providing an overpowering inside-outside
combination that led No. 8 Connecticut to a 117-67 rout of North Carolina-Asheville.
article.headline: Gordon scores 29 to lead Huskies' rout
article.linkText: UConn's inside-out power overwhelms NC Asheville
article.story:
HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- There was no energy shortage for No. 8 Connecticut on Saturday.

	   Ben Gordon topped the speedy Huskies with 29 points and Emeka
Okafor added 19 for an overpowering inside-outside combination that
led UConn to a 117-67 victory over North Carolina-Asheville.

	   Gordon set a tempo that the Bulldogs were unable to match and
Okafor dominated inside as he has all season.

	   "Coach runs us so much in practice we're able to run teams
down,'' Gordon said. "These games are confidence boosters.''

	   The win also was big boost for coach Jim Calhoun, who praised
his team's pressure, ball-sharing and speed. The Huskies got 43
points from their bench, including some key 3-pointers from
freshman Rashad Anderson.

	   "I'm more energized now because we played with so much
energy,'' Calhoun said. "We showed a little bit more of our depth.
We showed our speed and we mainly showed what we are good at.''

	   The Huskies (7-0) ran up their largest point total of the
season. Gordon hit 5-of-10 3-pointers and had nine assists, most
down low to Okafor.

	   The 6-foot-9 Okafor had 10 rebounds and has recorded a
double-double in all seven games. He had four of UConn's 10 blocks
and the Huskies outrebounded Asheville 46-32.

	   "He's so valuable to us,'' Gordon said of Okafor. "He's
elevated his offensive game tremendously and so he helps us on both
ends of the floor.''

	   Asheville tried various matchup defenses to hobble the Huskies,
but UConn blew by them.

	   "We were playing with such energy we just didn't recognize
it,'' Calhoun said. "We were playing so fast.''

	   The Bulldogs (3-4) were outscored 70-10 in the post. Ben
McGonagil, Asheville's 6-11 center, got into foul trouble quickly
against Okafor and spent most of the game playing with four fouls.
Asheville struggled inside with McGonagil on the bench.

	   "We don't have a whole lot of strength behind him,'' Asheville
coach Eddie Biedenbach said. "So they were able to run out of
there and pounded it inside.''

	   Alex Kragel led Asheville with 15 points and McGonagil had 12,
all in the second half. Andre Smith also had 12 points.

	   Denham Brown scored 15 for UConn and Anderson added 13, going
4-of-6 from 3-point range.

	   After a slow start, the Huskies' fast break got rolling late in
the first half just as the Bulldogs closed in on a nine-point
deficit. Smith hit consecutive jumpers for Asheville to pull the
Bulldogs to 27-25 with 6:28 left the half.

	   After that it was all UConn.

	   Okafor converted a three-point play to trigger a 20-2 run.
Gordon had nine points in the spurt. Smith got the Bulldogs' only
basket in the run, but hurt his left ankle on the shot and left
with 3:52 left.

	   Gordon's 3-pointer capped the run, giving UConn a 47-27 lead
with 1:09 left. The teams traded baskets down the stretch and UConn
took a 51-33 halftime lead.

	   Gordon opened the second half with a steal and a slam. His
teammates responded with 69 percent shooting in the period.

	   "We're a very versatile team,'' Okafor said. "We have a lot of
weapons and in games like these, you get to see more of them.''

	   Biedenbach and Bulldogs saw plenty.

	   "I would have liked to have made it a tougher game to see how
they are under pressure,'' Biedenbach said, "but they got
freewheeling and just kicked our tail.''
